      <lido:objectDescriptionWrap>
        <lido:objectDescriptionSet>
          <lido:descriptiveNoteValue xml:lang="en">From searches of H. van Os and M. Rinkleff-Reindersmeer it has been found that our paintings from two plane panels sawn-through are formed. Originally stood on the back of Lance Cross says the Angel of the Annunciation, and on the back of the Descent of the Holy Mother of the Annunciation. Along with the Entombment in the Staatliche Museen, Berlin-Dahlem and the Carrying of the Cross at the Louvre were these two panels once a whole, called the Orsini polyptych, to the coat of arms on the back of the Louvre painting. It is suspected can thus be that this was originally came to a trip altar with on the left panel the Carrying of, in the middle of the spear and the Deposition, and on the right the entombment. \ R When the shutters were closed one saw than at the one side the Annunciation and on the other arms of the Orsini's. In the foreground of the Deposition, much smaller than the other figures, the donator: a kneeling and praying bishop. J. Brink points out that this is probably going to the Franciscan Napoleone Orsini (1342 to Avignion), where Simone Martini, according to a report by Petrarch, was employed. (Catalog KMSKA Old Masters Paintings)</lido:descriptiveNoteValue>
        </lido:objectDescriptionSet>
